'''Senzan Seven Lucky Gods Pilgrimage''' (泉山七福神巡り, せんざんしちふくじんめぐり) is an event in which pilgrims visit seven sub-temples<ref>When extras are included, the total number becomes nine. The main hall of {{ill|Sennyūji|ja|泉涌寺}} is also counted as an extra.</ref> located within the mountain precincts of {{ill|Sennyū-ji|ja|泉涌寺}} in {{ill|Kyoto Prefecture|ja|京都府}} {{ill|Kyoto City|ja|京都市}} {{ill|Higashiyama Ward|ja|東山区}}. It is held annually on the second {{ill|Monday|ja|月曜日}} of {{ill|January|ja|1月}} ({{ill|Coming of Age Day|ja|成人の日}}) as a pilgrimage of the {{ill|Seven Lucky Gods|ja|七福神}}.<ref>[http://www.mitera.org/7huku.php Official site of Sennyūji – Senzan Seven Lucky Gods Pilgrimage]</ref><ref>Until {{ill|1999|ja|1999th year }} ({{ill|Heisei|ja|平成}}11), the event was held annually on {{ill|January 15|ja|1月15日}}, similar to Coming of Age Day.</ref>
== Overview == The belief in the Seven Lucky Gods is said to have originated in Kyoto during the {{ill|Muromachi Period|ja|室町時代}}, gradually spreading throughout Japan. It is believed that a New Year visit to the shrines brings good fortune. The Senzan Seven Lucky Gods Pilgrimage has been held every year on Coming of Age Day since {{ill|1951|ja|1951st year }} ({{ill|Showa|ja|昭和}}26), and it is regarded as a grand New Year tradition that grows more elaborate each year.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20161228215616/http://www.mitera.org/event.php Official Sennyūji site – Annual Events] (Archived as of December 28, 2016 from the {{ill|Internet Archive|ja|インターネットアーカイブ|lt=Archive|lt_ja=アーカイブ}})</ref>
On the day of the pilgrimage, participants carry the '''Fukuzasa''' – a talisman conferred at the first site, {{ill|Sokuseiin|ja|即成院}} – to which they attach additional auspicious items ({{ill|Auspicious Items|ja|縁起物}}). The Fukuzasa, made of evergreen bamboo leaves (the {{ill|Sasa|ja|ササ|lt=Sasa|lt_ja=笹}} that grow vertically, symbolizing rising fortune), is held as they sequentially visit the sub-temples along {{ill|Sennyūji Road|ja|泉涌寺道}}. The event traditionally attracts large crowds.
