[[sn:Senzan Seven Lucky Gods Pilgrimage]] [[ja:泉山七福神巡り]]

'''Senzan Seven Lucky Gods Pilgrimage''' (泉山七福神巡り, せんざんしちふくじんめぐり) is an event in which pilgrims visit seven sub-temples<ref>When extras are included, the total number becomes nine. The main hall of {{ill|Sennyūji|ja|泉涌寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sennyūji|qq=}} is also counted as an extra.</ref> located within the mountain precincts of {{ill|Sennyū-ji|ja|泉涌寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sennyū-ji|qq=}} in {{ill|Kyoto Prefecture|ja|京都府|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyoto Prefecture|qq=}} {{ill|Kyoto City|ja|京都市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyoto City|qq=}} {{ill|Higashiyama Ward|ja|東山区|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Higashiyama Ward|qq=}}. It is held annually on the second {{ill|Monday|ja|月曜日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Monday|qq=}} of {{ill|January|ja|1月|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/January|qq=}} ({{ill|Coming of Age Day|ja|成人の日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Coming of Age Day|qq=}}) as a pilgrimage of the {{ill|Seven Lucky Gods|ja|七福神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Seven Lucky Gods|qq=}}.<ref>[http://www.mitera.org/7huku.php Official site of Sennyūji – Senzan Seven Lucky Gods Pilgrimage]</ref><ref>Until {{ill|1999|ja|1999年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1999|qq=}} ({{ill|Heisei|ja|平成|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heisei|qq=}}11), the event was held annually on {{ill|January 15|ja|1月15日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/January 15|qq=}}, similar to Coming of Age Day.</ref>
== Overview == The belief in the Seven Lucky Gods is said to have originated in Kyoto during the {{ill|Muromachi Period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muromachi Period|qq=}}, gradually spreading throughout Japan. It is believed that a New Year visit to the shrines brings good fortune. The Senzan Seven Lucky Gods Pilgrimage has been held every year on Coming of Age Day since {{ill|1951|ja|1951st year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1951|qq=}} ({{ill|Showa|ja|昭和|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Showa|qq=}}26), and it is regarded as a grand New Year tradition that grows more elaborate each year.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20161228215616/http://www.mitera.org/event.php Official Sennyūji site – Annual Events] (Archived as of December 28, 2016 from the {{ill|Internet Archive|ja|インターネットアーカイブ|lt=Archive|lt_ja=アーカイブ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Internet Archive|qq=}})</ref>
On the day of the pilgrimage, participants carry the '''Fukuzasa''' – a talisman conferred at the first site, {{ill|Sokuseiin|ja|即成院|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sokuseiin|qq=}} – to which they attach additional auspicious items ({{ill|Auspicious Items|ja|縁起物|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Auspicious Items|qq=}}). The Fukuzasa, made of evergreen bamboo leaves (the {{ill|Sasa|ja|ササ|lt=Sasa|lt_ja=笹|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sasa|qq=}} that grow vertically, symbolizing rising fortune), is held as they sequentially visit the sub-temples along {{ill|Sennyūji Road|ja|泉涌寺道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sennyūji Road|qq=}}. The event traditionally attracts large crowds.
